GOOG <- read_csv("GOOG.csv", col_types = cols(Date = col_date(format = "%Y-%m-%d")))

Google Stock Price Plots

ggplot(GOOG) + aes(x=Date, y=Close) +
  geom_point()

ggplot(GOOG) + aes(x=Date, y=Close) +
  geom_line()

ggplot(GOOG) + aes(x=Date, y=Close) +
  geom_col()

ggplot(GOOG) + aes(x=Close, ) +
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ggplot(GOOG) + aes(x=Close, ) +
  geom_boxplot()

ggplot(GOOG) + aes(x=Date, y=Close) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line()

You have created many different pplots of the same data but some are more helpful than others. Based on the plots you created, which one do you find most useful and why?

I would go with the last chart we created. It shows the trend over time and clarifies those points. I don’t think averages help very much in Stock Prices because they are so volatile. The Line/Scatter plot looks the cleaniest and tells a story without over complicating it.

Google Stock Daily Proce Comparisons

ggplot(GOOG) +
  geom_line(aes(Date, High, color="High")) +
  geom_line(aes(Date, Low, color="Low"))

ggplot(GOOG) +
  geom_point(aes(Date, High, color="High")) +
  geom_point(aes(Date, Low, color="Low"))

ggplot(GOOG) +
  geom_line(aes(Date, Open, color="Open")) +
  geom_line(aes(Date, Close, color="Close"))

ggplot(GOOG) +
  geom_point(aes(Date, Open, color="Open")) +
  geom_point(aes(Date, Close, color="Close"))

ggplot(GOOG, aes(Date, Close)) +
  geom_area(color="black", fill="blue", alpha= .2)

ggplot(GOOG, aes(Date, Open)) +
  geom_area(color="blue", fill="green", alpha= .1)

MayPrice<- subset(GOOG, Date> "2020-04-30" & Date<"2020-06-01")
ggplot(MayPrice, aes(Date, Close)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_text( aes(label= round(Close)), size=3, vjust= -1)

AprilPrice<- subset(GOOG, Date> "2020-03-31" & Date<"2020-05-01")
ggplot(AprilPrice, aes(Date, Open)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_text(aes(label= round(Open)), size=2, vjust=1.5 )
